  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Strengthening National Capacity to Address the Environmental Impacts of Humanitarian Responses to Population Displacement in Selected Countries</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">This project responds to the call to address the large movements of displaced people and migrants by the General Assembly of the United Nations in its Declaration of High Level Dialogue on International Migration and Development (2013), which highlighted the need to examine the role that environmental factors play in migration. The project seeks to provide evidence on the relationship between humanitarian responses to human mobility and the impacts to the environment that are involved in the response. Human mobility, in all its forms, has environmental impact, even if it is not easily visible; humanitarian response to the needs of migrants and refugees leaves an environmental footprint. These considerations, in addition to the limited capacity of local governments in environmental management and service provision, are conditions that exacerbate humanitarian needs, especially among the most vulnerable groups such as female heads of household, elderly, and unaccompanied children. IOM and the UN Evaluation Group established a strategic partnership for the implementation of this project, which will serve as a platform to explore in more detail the relationship between the environment and human mobility.</narrative>
  </description>
